Moon Palace is definitively the best Chinese food in Chicago. I have been a regular patron of Moon Palace for almost 20 years now and I am amazed at how they never fail to consistently meet (and at times exceed) my expectations. Serving sizes were on the small side and an 18% gratuity was automatically added even though there were only 5 of us. The shrimp toast is delicious but the rest of the food was just ok. I paid $15 for Happy Family but have had much better for $9. A small serving of egg drop soup was $4 while in most other restaurants it's between $2 and $3 for a small bowl. I am honestly thinking people were paid to write such positive reviews. Today was the first time going with my family. We get there and everything looks pretty clean and nice. It was pretty much empty and we  arrived there around 4pm. My family and I were pretty excited to try such a positively reviewed place. To my surprise, after being served what we ordered, I was very saddened and disappointed with the poor quality of the food. Chow mein was half cooked and had a toasted like quality. It literally looked like ramen before being cooked!! We were charged for a plate we never received and once we spoke to one of the servers, they seemed annoyed and started speaking their own native language. They didn’t apologize , they seemed very upset, however we were being charged $18 for something we didn’t receive! Also, we didn’t know they had drinks, we were only served water. We also got a sauce that LITERALLY TASTED LIKE NAIL POLISH REMOVER! It was insane!!! I was so disappointed with the quality in general. I swear I have never tasted something so bad and my family and I are not picky at all. We ate only a certain portion of food because we didn’t want to seem rude. This was the worst experience. The server we had almost threw the plate at us. Her way of serving was pretty harsh and wasn’t really amigable. This was our first and LAST time in this place!!

I’m not sure why this place is so highly rated. I’m all of Chinatown or Chicago in general, there are much better more traditional Chinese restaurants. It was overpriced for what it was and the soup I had was pretty salty. I hated that the menu simply said “Beef Noodle Soup” and not tell you much of what was in it or maybe put the actual name. I’ve been to far better Chinese places for much cheaper too. It seemed like it was trying to be upscale. If you’re actually Asian and don’t want gross Americanized, salty food, don’t come here. It’s one of those places you walk into and just see a ton of older people and immediately know the quality of the restaurant.  That being said the service was fine and they were accommodating for a vegetarian friend and made him orange tofu instead of chicken. Portions aren’t bad but I didn’t think the taste was all that good for the cost.
